# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: zfs-filesystem
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:zfs-filesystem/copy-on-write] Copy-on-write finds its main use in operating systems, sharing the physical memory of computers running multiple processes, in the implementation of the fork() system call.
[src:zfs-filesystem/copy-on-write] Typically, the new process does not modify any memory and immediately executes a new process, replacing the address space entirely.
[src:zfs-filesystem/copy-on-write] It would waste processor time and memory to copy all of the old process's memory during the fork only to immediately discard the copy.
[src:zfs-filesystem/copy-on-write] Copy-on-write can be implemented efficiently using the page table by marking certain pages of memory as read-only and keeping a count of the number of references to the page.
[src:zfs-filesystem/copy-on-write] When data is written to these pages, the operating-system kernel intercepts the write attempt and allocates a new physical page, initialized with the copy-on-write data, although the allocation can be skipped if there is only one reference.
[src:zfs-filesystem/copy-on-write] The kernel then updates the page table with the new (writable) page, decrements the number of references, and performs the write.
[src:zfs-filesystem/copy-on-write] The new allocation ensures that a change in the memory of one process is not visible in another's.
[src:zfs-filesystem/copy-on-write] The copy-on-write technique can be extended to support efficient memory allocation by keeping one page of physical memory filled with zeros.
[src:zfs-filesystem/copy-on-write] When the memory is allocated, all the pages returned refer to the page of zeros and are all marked copy-on-write.
[src:zfs-filesystem/copy-on-write] This way, physical memory is not allocated for the process until data is written, allowing processes to reserve more virtual memory than physical memory and use memory sparsely, at the risk of running out of virtual address space.
[src:zfs-filesystem/copy-on-write] The combined algorithm is similar to demand paging.
[src:zfs-filesystem/copy-on-write] Copy-on-write pages are also used in the Linux kernel's same-page merging feature.
[src:zfs-filesystem/copy-on-write] COW is also used in library, application, and system code.
[src:zfs-filesystem/copy-on-write] In the PHP programming language, all types except references are implemented as copy-on-write.
[src:zfs-filesystem/copy-on-write] For example, strings and arrays are passed by reference, but when modified, they are duplicated if they have non-zero reference counts.
[src:zfs-filesystem/copy-on-write] This allows them to act as value types without the performance problems of copying on assignment or making them immutable.
[src:zfs-filesystem/copy-on-write] In the Qt framework, many types are copy-on-write ("implicitly shared" in Qt's terms).
[src:zfs-filesystem/copy-on-write] Qt uses atomic compare-and-swap operations to increment or decrement the internal reference counter.
[src:zfs-filesystem/copy-on-write] Since the copies are cheap, Qt types can often be safely used by multiple threads without the need of locking mechanisms such as mutexes.
[src:zfs-filesystem/copy-on-write] The benefits of COW are thus valid in both single- and multithreaded systems.
[src:zfs-filesystem/copy-on-write] In Docker, a set of software for implementing operating-system level virtualization, docker images are built in a layered format, with lower layers being read-only and the upper layer available for editing.
[src:zfs-filesystem/copy-on-write] Creating a new image which shares the same base layers as another image does not copy the layers, but instead follows COW principles and allows the two images to share layers until one is edited.
[src:zfs-filesystem/copy-on-write] COW is used as the underlying mechanism in file systems like ZFS, Btrfs, ReFS, and Bcachefs, as well as in logical volume management and database servers such as Microsoft SQL Server.
[src:zfs-filesystem/copy-on-write] In traditional file systems, modifying a file overwrites the original data blocks in place.
[src:zfs-filesystem/copy-on-write] In a copy-on-write (COW) file system, the original blocks remain unchanged.
[src:zfs-filesystem/copy-on-write] When part of a file is modified, only the affected blocks are written to new locations, and metadata is updated to point to them, preserving the original version until it’s no longer needed.
[src:zfs-filesystem/copy-on-write] This approach enables features like snapshots, which capture the state of a file at a specific time without consuming much additional space.
[src:zfs-filesystem/copy-on-write] Snapshots typically store only the modified data and are kept close to the original.
[src:zfs-filesystem/copy-on-write] However, they are considered a weak form of incremental backup and cannot replace a full backup.
[src:zfs-filesystem/copy-on-write] In order to create and start new containers quickly, container engines doing OS-level virtualization often perform copy-on-write in storage, either block-level copy-on-write (as described above) or file-level copy-on-write.
[src:zfs-filesystem/copy-on-write] Some but not all filesystems support file-level copy-on-write as part of union mounting, including OverlayFS, aufs, GlusterFS, and UnionFS.
[src:zfs-filesystem/openzfs] One of the main capabilities of OpenZFS is self-healing.
[src:zfs-filesystem/openzfs] The file system can detect and correct errors while in use, without the need for a dedicated file system checker.
[src:zfs-filesystem/openzfs] This feature makes it suitable for mission-critical applications that require high availability.
[src:zfs-filesystem/openzfs] OpenZFS is mainly used in enterprise and data center environments, as well as consumer devices like network-attached storage (NAS) devices, where data reliability and safety is essential.
[src:zfs-filesystem/openzfs] While initially designed for Solaris, development has since focused on Linux, while ports exist for various BSD distributions and macOS.
[src:zfs-filesystem/openzfs] Unlike Oracle ZFS, OpenZFS is licensed under the Common Development and Distribution License (CDDL), enabling both open-source and commercial use of the file system.
[src:zfs-filesystem/openzfs] Founding members of OpenZFS include Matt Ahrens, one of the main architects of ZFS.
[src:zfs-filesystem/openzfs] In 2020, the codebases of OpenZFS and ZFS on Linux, a kernel module allowing ZFS to be used on Linux, were merged and released as OpenZFS 2.0, allowing other non-Linux operating systems to receive the various improvements that the Linux driver had incorporated over time.
[src:zfs-filesystem/openzfs] The ZFS file system was originally developed by Sun Microsystems for the Solaris operating system.
[src:zfs-filesystem/openzfs] The ZFS source code was released in 2005 under the Common Development and Distribution License as part of the OpenSolaris operating system, and it was later ported to other operating systems and environments.
[src:zfs-filesystem/openzfs] As a workaround, FUSE, a framework that allows file systems to run in userspace, was used on Linux as a separation layer for which the licensing issues did not apply, although with a set of its own issues that includes a performance penalty.
[src:zfs-filesystem/openzfs] However, the April 2016 release of Ubuntu 16.04 LTS includes ZFS as a kernel module.
[src:zfs-filesystem/openzfs] In the release version of Mac OS X 10.5, ZFS was available in read-only mode from the command line, which lacks the possibility to create z-pools or write to them.
[src:zfs-filesystem/openzfs] Before the 10.5 release, Apple released the "ZFS Beta Seed v1.1", which allowed read-write access and the creation of z-pools; however, the installer for the "ZFS Beta Seed v1.1" has been reported to only work on version 10.5.0, and has not been updated for version 10.5.1 and above.
[src:zfs-filesystem/openzfs] In August 2007, Apple opened a ZFS project on their Mac OS Forge web site.
[src:zfs-filesystem/openzfs] On that site, Apple provided the source code and binaries of their port of ZFS which includes read-write access, but without an installer.
[src:zfs-filesystem/openzfs] In October 2009, Apple discontinued development of the ZFS project on Mac OS Forge with no explanation.
[src:zfs-filesystem/openzfs] Apple removed everything but the CDDL-licensed portion of the source code for their final build of the ZFS project, code named "10a286".
[src:zfs-filesystem/openzfs] Complete ZFS support was originally advertised as a feature of Snow Leopard Server before launch, but by the time the operating system was released all references to this feature had been removed from its features page.
[src:zfs-filesystem/openzfs] Apple's "10a286" source code release, and versions of the previously released source and binaries, have been preserved and new development had been adopted by the MacZFS project to continue development outside of Apple.
[src:zfs-filesystem/openzfs] As of July 2012, Mac ZFS implements z-pool version 8 and ZFS version 2, released with the October 2008 release of Solaris.
[src:zfs-filesystem/openzfs] Additional historical information and commentary can be found on the Mac ZFS web site and FAQ.
[src:zfs-filesystem/openzfs] However, the project ceased development in mid 2013 with a message asking users to switch to *Open ZFS on OSX* (abbreviated to *O3X*).
[src:zfs-filesystem/openzfs] Although the ZFS filesystem supports Linux-based operating systems, difficulties arise for Linux distribution maintainers wishing to provide native support for ZFS in their products due to legal incompatibilities between the ZFS's CDDL license and the GPL license used by the Linux kernel.
[src:zfs-filesystem/openzfs] To enable ZFS support within Linux, a loadable kernel module containing the CDDL-licensed ZFS code must be compiled and loaded into the kernel.
[src:zfs-filesystem/openzfs] According to the Free Software Foundation, the wording of the GPL license legally prohibits redistribution of the resulting product as a derivative work, though this viewpoint has caused some controversy.
[src:zfs-filesystem/openzfs] One potential workaround to licensing incompatibility was trialed in 2006, with an experimental port of the ZFS code to Linux's FUSE system.
[src:zfs-filesystem/openzfs] The filesystem ran entirely in userspace instead of being integrated into the Linux kernel, and was therefore not considered a derivative work of the kernel.
[src:zfs-filesystem/openzfs] This approach was functional, but suffered from significant performance penalties when compared with integrating the filesystem as a native kernel module running in kernel space.
[src:zfs-filesystem/openzfs] As of 2016, the ZFS on FUSE project appears to be defunct, as the ZFS on Linux kernel driver has prevailed over the userspace one.
[src:zfs-filesystem/openzfs] As of August 2014, ZFS on Linux uses the OpenZFS pool version number 5000, which indicates that the features it supports are defined via feature flags.
[src:zfs-filesystem/openzfs] This pool version is an unchanging number that is expected to never conflict with version numbers given by Oracle.
[src:zfs-filesystem/openzfs] Another native port for Linux was developed by KQ InfoTech in 2010.
[src:zfs-filesystem/openzfs] This port used the *zvol* implementation from the Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory as a starting point.
[src:zfs-filesystem/openzfs] A release supporting *zpool* v28 was announced in January 2011.
[src:zfs-filesystem/openzfs] In April 2011, KQ Infotech was acquired by sTec, Inc., and their work on ZFS ceased.
[src:zfs-filesystem/openzfs] Source code of this port can be found on GitHub.
[src:zfs-filesystem/openzfs] The work of KQ InfoTech was ultimately integrated into the LLNL's native port of ZFS for Linux.
[src:zfs-filesystem/openzfs] While license incompatibilities may arise with the distribution of compiled binaries containing ZFS code, it is generally agreed that distribution of the source code itself is not affected by this.
[src:zfs-filesystem/openzfs] In Gentoo Linux, configuring a ZFS root filesystem is well documented and the required packages can be installed from its package repository.
[src:zfs-filesystem/openzfs] Slackware also provides documentation on supporting ZFS, both as a kernel module and built into the kernel.
[src:zfs-filesystem/openzfs] The question of the CDDL license's compatibility with the GPL license resurfaced in 2015, when the Linux distribution Ubuntu announced that it intended to make precompiled OpenZFS binary kernel modules available to end-users directly from the distribution's official package repositories.
[src:zfs-filesystem/openzfs] In 2016, Ubuntu announced that a legal review resulted in the conclusion that providing support for ZFS via a binary kernel module was not in violation of the provisions of the GPL license.
[src:zfs-filesystem/openzfs] Other organizations such as the Software Freedom Law Center followed Ubuntu's conclusion, while the FSF and SFC reiterated their opposing views.
[src:zfs-filesystem/openzfs] Ubuntu 16.04 LTS ("Xenial Xerus"), released on April 21, 2016, allows the user to install the OpenZFS binary packages directly from the Ubuntu software repositories.
[src:zfs-filesystem/openzfs] As of 2024, no legal challenge has been brought against Canonical regarding the distribution of these packages.
[src:zfs-filesystem/openzfs] As of 2019, Ubuntu supports experimental installation of ZFS as a root filesystem, starting with the 19.10 release ("Eoan Ermine"), to support coexistence of a nearly pure ZFS OS with GRUB and other operating systems on the same disk.
[src:zfs-filesystem/openzfs] A version of TrueNAS by iXsystems, based on Debian Linux.
[src:zfs-filesystem/openzfs] As with TrueNAS Core (based on FreeBSD), it uses OpenZFS for storage and adds a variety of additional features.
[src:zfs-filesystem/openzfs] These include expanded device driver support, KVM virtual machines, PCIe passthrough and container support via Kubernetes and Docker.
[src:zfs-filesystem/openzfs] Furthermore, it allows clustered Docker and ZFS via gluster.
[src:zfs-filesystem/openzfs] Information about the current release can be found at the iXsystems Software Status page.
[src:zfs-filesystem/openzfs] The "Scale" branding was officially dropped from the name with the release of TrueNAS 25.04, Fangtooth, which only has a Linux release.
[src:zfs-filesystem/openzfs] A port of open source ZFS was attempted in 2010 but after a hiatus of over one year development ceased in 2012.
[src:zfs-filesystem/openzfs] In October 2017, a new port of OpenZFS was announced by Jörgen Lundman at OpenZFS Developer Summit.
[src:zfs-filesystem/openzfs] A newer open source port of ZFS which is considered a BETA release, can be found also on GitHub.
[src:zfs-filesystem/openzfs] Originally, version numbers of the pool and file system were incremented as new features were introduced, in order to designate the on-disk file system format and available features.
[src:zfs-filesystem/openzfs] This worked well when a single entity controlled the development of ZFS, and this versioning scheme is still in use with the ZFS in Oracle Solaris.
[src:zfs-filesystem/openzfs] In a more distributed development model, having a single version number is far from ideal as all implementations of OpenZFS would need to agree on all changes to the on-disk file system format.
[src:zfs-filesystem/openzfs] The solution selected by OpenZFS was to introduce *feature flags* as a new versioning system that tags on-disk format changes with unique names, and supports both completely independent format changes and format changes that depend on each other.
[src:zfs-filesystem/openzfs] A pool can be moved and used between OpenZFS implementations as long as all feature flags in use by the pool are supported by both implementations.
[src:zfs-filesystem/openzfs] In OpenZFS, the pool version is permanently set to 5000, signifying that the pool indicates new features by setting or unsetting ZFS feature flags rather than by incrementing the pool version.
[src:zfs-filesystem/openzfs] The number 5000 was chosen because it is expected to never conflict with version numbers given by Oracle.
[src:zfs-filesystem/openzfs] Legacy version numbers still exist for pool versions 1–28.
[src:zfs-filesystem/openzfs] Future on-disk format changes are enabled / disabled independently via these feature flags.
[src:zfs-filesystem/openzfs] Legacy version numbers still exist for pool versions 1–28, and are implied by the pool version 5000; the initial proposal was to use 1000 as the pool version.
[src:zfs-filesystem/openzfs] Future on-disk format changes are enabled and disabled independently via feature flags.
[src:zfs-filesystem/openzfs] For example, feature@com.foocompany:async_destroy is a valid property name, and it could be shortened to feature@async_destroy.
[src:zfs-filesystem/openzfs] Each pool feature can be in either *disabled*, *enabled*, or *active* state.
[src:zfs-filesystem/openzfs] Disabled features are those that will not be used, and no on-disk format changes will be made; as a result, such features are backward-compatible.
[src:zfs-filesystem/openzfs] Enabled features are those that will be used, no on-disk format changes have been made yet, but the software may make the changes at any time; such features are still backward-compatible.
[src:zfs-filesystem/openzfs] Active features are those that have made backward-incompatible on-disk format changes to the pool.
[src:zfs-filesystem/openzfs] When any pool feature is enabled, legacy version of the pool is automatically upgraded to 5000 and any other prerequisite features are also enabled.
[src:zfs-filesystem/openzfs] By default, new pools are created with all supported features enabled.
[src:zfs-filesystem/openzfs] In general, state of a feature can be changed from *active* back to *enabled*, undoing that way performed on-disk format changes and making the pool compatible again with an older OpenZFS implementation; however, for some features that might not be possible.
[src:zfs-filesystem/openzfs] On-disk format changes can be associated with either *features for write* or *features for read*.
[src:zfs-filesystem/openzfs] The former are the features that an OpenZFS implementation must support to be capable of writing to the pool, while supporting such features is not mandatory for opening the pool in read-only mode.
[src:zfs-filesystem/openzfs] The latter are the features that an OpenZFS implementation must support to be able to read from the pool or to just open it, because opening a pool is not possible without actually reading from it.
[src:zfs-filesystem/openzfs] For example, async_destroy feature adds a new on-disk data structure to keep track of freed datasets, but an OpenZFS implementation does not need to know about this data structure to access the pool in read-only mode.
[src:zfs-filesystem/openzfs] Additionally, writing to a pool that has some features in *active* state is not possible by an OpenZFS implementation that does not support the same features.
[src:zfs-filesystem/openzfs] Historically, OpenZFS has been implemented as a core ZFS code, with each operating system's team adapting it to fit into their projects.
[src:zfs-filesystem/openzfs] This led in some cases to feature stagnation and divergence of features and command lines, as different operating systems developed divergent features and bug fixes, often for a single platform rather than across all platforms.
[src:zfs-filesystem/openzfs] Over time, new feature development shifted from Illumos to Linux.
[src:zfs-filesystem/openzfs] These new features and fixes then had to be backported to Illumos before they could be re-ported for FreeBSD.
[src:zfs-filesystem/openzfs] But this was difficult because the Linux version also included many smaller changes, which were hard to disentangle.
[src:zfs-filesystem/openzfs] In 2018, it was agreed that OpenZFS development would be overhauled to remedy these issues.
[src:zfs-filesystem/openzfs] Rather than try to import all the Linux changes to other platforms piecemeal, the entire Linux ZFS code would be 'pivoted' as a whole, with other platforms being based on the more actively developed Linux version.
[src:zfs-filesystem/openzfs] A wide range of ported and new features, including many long-desired enhancements, would also be rolled out or ported across platforms, and future changes would be discussed across platforms before being implemented.
[src:zfs-filesystem/openzfs] The plans included appropriate porting layers to prevent Linux, GPL or Linux-KPI shim code from being introduced to other platform kernels.
[src:zfs-filesystem/raid-z] Although all RAID implementations differ from the specification to some extent, some companies and open-source projects have developed **non-standard RAID implementations** that differ substantially from the standard.
[src:zfs-filesystem/raid-z] Additionally, there are non-RAID drive architectures, providing configurations of multiple hard drives not referred to by RAID acronyms.
[src:zfs-filesystem/raid-z] RDP is invented by NetApp, which also uses it in an unusual system of parity storage called **RAID-DP** (RAID Double Parity).
[src:zfs-filesystem/raid-z] The "row" parity is stored on a dedicated disk like in RAID 4, but the "diagonal" parity is stored on a distributed way like in RAID 5.
[src:zfs-filesystem/raid-z] The technique can be considered RAID 6 in the broad SNIA definition and has the same failure characteristics as RAID 6.
[src:zfs-filesystem/raid-z] RDP is very CPU-efficient compared to earlier schemes (Reed-Solomon with or without Anvin's optimization, EVENODD).
[src:zfs-filesystem/raid-z] The performance penalty of RAID-DP is typically under 2% when compared to a similar RAID 4 configuration.
[src:zfs-filesystem/raid-z] RAID 7.*m* has been used to describe an erasure coding system with *m* extra drives and able to tolerate the loss of *m* drives.
[src:zfs-filesystem/raid-z] In this scheme, RAID 5 would be RAID 7.1 and RAID 6 would be RAID 7.2.
[src:zfs-filesystem/raid-z] Alternatively, RAID N+M refers to N regular data drives with M redundancy drives, being able to recover all the data when any M drives fail.
[src:zfs-filesystem/raid-z] It is possible to support a far greater number of drives by choosing the parity function more carefully.
[src:zfs-filesystem/raid-z] The issue we face is to ensure that a system of equations over the finite field $\mathbb {Z} _{2}$ has a unique solution.
[src:zfs-filesystem/raid-z] To do this, we can use the theory of polynomial equations over finite fields.
[src:zfs-filesystem/raid-z] Consider the Galois field $GF(m)$ with $m=2^{k}$ .
[src:zfs-filesystem/raid-z] This field is isomorphic to a polynomial field $F_{2}[x]/(p(x))$ for a suitable irreducible polynomial $p(x)$ of degree k over $\mathbb {Z} _{2}$ .
[src:zfs-filesystem/raid-z] Let $\mathbf {D} _{0},...,\mathbf {D} _{n-1}\in GF(m)$ correspond to the stripes of data across hard drives encoded as field elements in this manner.
[src:zfs-filesystem/raid-z] We will use $\oplus$ to denote addition in the field, and concatenation to denote multiplication.
[src:zfs-filesystem/raid-z] The reuse of $\oplus$ is intentional: this is because addition in the finite field $\mathbb {Z} _{2}$ represents to the XOR operator, so computing the sum of two elements is equivalent to computing XOR on the polynomial coefficients.
[src:zfs-filesystem/raid-z] A generator of a field is an element of the field such that $g^{i}$ is different for each non-negative $i<m-1$ .
[src:zfs-filesystem/raid-z] This means each element of the field, except the value 0 , can be written as a power of $g.$ A finite field is guaranteed to have at least one generator.
[src:zfs-filesystem/raid-z] As before, the first checksum $\mathbf {P}$ is just the XOR of each stripe, though interpreted now as a polynomial.
[src:zfs-filesystem/raid-z] The effect of $g^{i}$ can be thought of as the action of a carefully chosen linear feedback shift register on the data chunk.
[src:zfs-filesystem/raid-z] If one data chunk is lost, the situation is similar to the one before.
[src:zfs-filesystem/raid-z] In the case of two lost data chunks, we can compute the recovery formulas algebraically.
[src:zfs-filesystem/raid-z] We can solve for $D_{i}$ in the second equation and plug it into the first to find $D_{j}=(g^{m-i+j}\oplus 1)^{-1}(g^{m-i}B\oplus A)$ , and then $D_{i}=A\oplus D_{j}$ .
[src:zfs-filesystem/raid-z] Unlike **P**, The computation of **Q** is relatively CPU intensive, as it involves polynomial multiplication in $F_{2}[x]/(p(x))$ .
[src:zfs-filesystem/raid-z] This can be mitigated through a hardware implementation (ASIC or FPGA).
[src:zfs-filesystem/raid-z] Unfortunately Anvin's Vandermonde matrix solutions only work up to triple parity; for beyond, a Cauchy matrix construction is required.
[src:zfs-filesystem/raid-z] SSSE3, AVX2, and other SIMD methods remain applicable.
[src:zfs-filesystem/raid-z] RAID 5E, RAID 5EE, and RAID 6E (with the added *E* standing for *Enhanced*) generally refer to variants of RAID 5 or 6 with an integrated hot-spare drive, where the spare drive is an active part of the block rotation scheme.
[src:zfs-filesystem/raid-z] This spreads I/O across all drives, including the spare, thus reducing the load on each drive, increasing performance.
[src:zfs-filesystem/raid-z] It does, however, prevent sharing the spare drive among multiple arrays, which is occasionally desirable.
[src:zfs-filesystem/raid-z] Intel Matrix RAID (a feature of Intel Rapid Storage Technology) is a feature (not a RAID level) present in the ICH6R and subsequent Southbridge chipsets from Intel, accessible and configurable via the RAID BIOS setup utility.
[src:zfs-filesystem/raid-z] Matrix RAID supports as few as two physical disks or as many as the controller supports.
[src:zfs-filesystem/raid-z] The distinguishing feature of Matrix RAID is that it allows any assortment of RAID 0, 1, 5, or 10 volumes in the array, to which a controllable (and identical) portion of each disk is allocated.
[src:zfs-filesystem/raid-z] As such, a Matrix RAID array can improve both performance and data integrity.
[src:zfs-filesystem/raid-z] A practical instance of this would use a small RAID 0 (stripe) volume for the operating system, program, and paging files; second larger RAID 1 (mirror) volume would store critical data.
[src:zfs-filesystem/raid-z] The software RAID subsystem provided by the Linux kernel, called md, supports the creation of both classic (nested) RAID 1+0 arrays, and non-standard RAID arrays that use a single-level RAID layout with some additional features.
[src:zfs-filesystem/raid-z] The standard "near" layout, in which each chunk is repeated *n* times in a *k*-way stripe array, is equivalent to the standard RAID 10 arrangement, but it does not require that *n* evenly divides *k*.
[src:zfs-filesystem/raid-z] The four-drive example is identical to a standard RAID 1+0 array, while the three-drive example is a software implementation of RAID 1E.
[src:zfs-filesystem/raid-z] The two-drive example is equivalent to RAID 1.
[src:zfs-filesystem/raid-z] The driver also supports a "far" layout, in which all the drives are divided into *f* sections.
[src:zfs-filesystem/raid-z] All the chunks are repeated in each section but are switched in groups (for example, in pairs).
[src:zfs-filesystem/raid-z] "Far" layout is designed for offering striping performance on a mirrored array; sequential reads can be striped, as in RAID 0 configurations.
[src:zfs-filesystem/raid-z] Random reads are somewhat faster, while sequential and random writes offer about equal speed to other mirrored RAID configurations.
[src:zfs-filesystem/raid-z] "Far" layout performs well for systems in which reads are more frequent than writes, which is a common case.
[src:zfs-filesystem/raid-z] For a comparison, regular RAID 1 as provided by Linux software RAID, does not stripe reads, but can perform reads in parallel.
[src:zfs-filesystem/raid-z] The md driver also supports an "offset" layout, in which each stripe is repeated *o* times and offset by *f* (far) devices.
[src:zfs-filesystem/raid-z] It is also possible to combine "near" and "offset" layouts (but not "far" and "offset").
[src:zfs-filesystem/raid-z] In the examples above, *k* is the number of drives, while *n#*, *f#*, and *o#* are given as parameters to mdadm's --layout option.
[src:zfs-filesystem/raid-z] Linux software RAID (Linux kernel's md driver) also supports creation of standard RAID 0, 1, 4, 5, and 6 configurations.
[src:zfs-filesystem/raid-z] Some RAID 1 implementations treat arrays with more than two disks differently, creating a non-standard RAID level known as **RAID 1E**.
[src:zfs-filesystem/raid-z] In this layout, data striping is combined with mirroring, by mirroring each written stripe to one of the remaining disks in the array.
[src:zfs-filesystem/raid-z] Usable capacity of a RAID 1E array is 50% of the total capacity of all drives forming the array; if drives of different sizes are used, only the portions equal to the size of smallest member are utilized on each drive.
[src:zfs-filesystem/raid-z] One of the benefits of RAID 1E over usual RAID 1 mirrored pairs is that the performance of random read operations remains above the performance of a single drive even in a degraded array.
[src:zfs-filesystem/raid-z] The ZFS filesystem provides *RAID-Z*, a data/parity distribution scheme similar to RAID 5, but using dynamic stripe width: every block is its own RAID stripe, regardless of blocksize, resulting in every RAID-Z write being a full-stripe write.
[src:zfs-filesystem/raid-z] This, when combined with the copy-on-write transactional semantics of ZFS, eliminates the write hole error.
[src:zfs-filesystem/raid-z] RAID-Z is also faster than traditional RAID 5 because it does not need to perform the usual read–modify–write sequence.
[src:zfs-filesystem/raid-z] RAID-Z does not require any special hardware, such as NVRAM for reliability, or write buffering for performance.
[src:zfs-filesystem/raid-z] Given the dynamic nature of RAID-Z's stripe width, RAID-Z reconstruction must traverse the filesystem metadata to determine the actual RAID-Z geometry.
[src:zfs-filesystem/raid-z] This would be impossible if the filesystem and the RAID array were separate products, whereas it becomes feasible when there is an integrated view of the logical and physical structure of the data.
[src:zfs-filesystem/raid-z] Going through the metadata means that ZFS can validate every block against its 256-bit checksum as it goes, whereas traditional RAID products usually cannot do this.
[src:zfs-filesystem/raid-z] Then, it repairs the damaged data and returns good data to the requestor.
[src:zfs-filesystem/raid-z] Windows Home Server Drive Extender is a specialized case of JBOD RAID 1 implemented at the file system level.
[src:zfs-filesystem/raid-z] Microsoft announced in 2011 that Drive Extender would no longer be included as part of Windows Home Server Version 2, Windows Home Server 2011 (codename VAIL).
[src:zfs-filesystem/raid-z] As a result, there has been a third-party vendor move to fill the void left by DE.
[src:zfs-filesystem/raid-z] Included competitors are Division M, the developers of Drive Bender, and StableBit's DrivePool.
[src:zfs-filesystem/raid-z] BeyondRaid offers a RAID 6–like feature and can perform hash-based compression using 160-bit SHA-1 hashes to maximize storage efficiency.
[src:zfs-filesystem/raid-z] Unraid is a proprietary Linux-based operating system optimized for media file storage.
[src:zfs-filesystem/raid-z] Unfortunately Unraid doesn't provide information about its storage technology, but some say its parity array is a rewrite of the mdadm module.
[src:zfs-filesystem/raid-z] Disadvantages include closed-source code, high price, slower write performance than a single disk and bottlenecks when multiple drives are written concurrently.
[src:zfs-filesystem/raid-z] However, Unraid allows support of a cache pool which can dramatically speed up the write performance.
[src:zfs-filesystem/raid-z] Cache pool data can be temporarily protected using Btrfs RAID 1 until Unraid moves it to the array based on a schedule set within the software.
[src:zfs-filesystem/raid-z] In OpenBSD, CRYPTO is an encrypting discipline for the softraid subsystem.
[src:zfs-filesystem/raid-z] It encrypts data on a single chunk to provide for data confidentiality.
[src:zfs-filesystem/raid-z] RAID 1C provides both redundancy and encryption.
[src:zfs-filesystem/raid-z] Some filesystems, such as Btrfs, and ZFS/OpenZFS (with per-dataset copies=1|2|3 property), support creating multiple copies of the same data on a single drive or disks pool, protecting from individual bad sectors, but not from large numbers of bad sectors or complete drive failure.
[src:zfs-filesystem/raid-z] This allows some of the benefits of RAID on computers that can only accept a single drive, such as laptops.
[src:zfs-filesystem/raid-z] Declustered Parity RAID allows for arbitrarily sized disk arrays while reducing the overhead to clients when recovering from disk failures.
[src:zfs-filesystem/raid-z] It uniformly spreads or declusters user data, redundancy information, and spare space across all disks of a declustered array.
[src:zfs-filesystem/raid-z] Under traditional RAID, an entire disk storage system of, say, 100 disks would be split into multiple arrays each of, say, 10 disks holding 8 data and 2 parity chunks.
[src:zfs-filesystem/raid-z] By contrast, under declustered parity RAID, the entire storage system is used to make one array.
[src:zfs-filesystem/raid-z] Every data and parity chunk is written to a different drive, as with standard RAID-5/6, but logically adjacent data and its redundancy can be spread arbitrarily across different drives within the array (though may be kept linear for some region to avoid seeking for sequential read/write operations).
[src:zfs-filesystem/raid-z] When a disk fails, missing data is rebuilt using all the operational disks in the array, the bandwidth of which is greater than that of the fewer disks of a conventional RAID group.
[src:zfs-filesystem/raid-z] Furthermore, if an additional disk fault occurs during a rebuild, the number of impacted tracks requiring repair is markedly less than the previous failure and less than the constant rebuild overhead of a conventional array.
[src:zfs-filesystem/raid-z] The decrease in declustered rebuild impact and client overhead can be a factor of three to four times less than a conventional RAID, scaling with the number of drives in the array.
[src:zfs-filesystem/raid-z] File system performance becomes less dependent upon the speed of any single rebuilding storage array.
[src:zfs-filesystem/raid-z] Declustered Parity RAID is used by many vendors of high-performance RAID arrays, including IBM,, Data Direct Networks DCR, and others.
[src:zfs-filesystem/raid-z] Dynamic disk pooling (DDP), also known as D-RAID, maintains performance even when up to 2 drives fail simultaneously.
[src:zfs-filesystem/raid-z] DDP is a high performance type of declustered RAID.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] user sees this as a single volume, containing an NTFS-formatted drive of their data, and NTFS is not necessarily aware of the manipulations that may be required (such as reading from/writing to the cache drive or rebuilding the RAID array if a disk fails).
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] The management of the individual devices and their presentation as a single device is distinct from the management of the files held on that apparent device.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] ZFS is unusual because, unlike most other storage systems, it unifies both of these roles and *acts as both the volume manager and the file system*.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] Therefore, it has complete knowledge of both the physical disks and volumes (including their status, condition, and logical arrangement into volumes) as well as of all the files stored on them.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] ZFS is designed to ensure (subject to sufficient data redundancy) that data stored on disks cannot be lost due to physical errors, misprocessing by the hardware or operating system, or bit rot events and data corruption that may happen over time.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] Its complete control of the storage system is used to ensure that every step, whether related to file management or disk management, is verified, confirmed, corrected if needed, and optimized, in a way that the storage controller cards and separate volume and file systems cannot achieve.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] ZFS also includes a mechanism for dataset and pool-level snapshots and replication, including snapshot cloning, which is described by the FreeBSD documentation as one of its "most powerful features" with functionality that "even other file systems with snapshot functionality lack".
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] Snapshots can be rolled back "live" or previous file system states can be viewed, even on very large file systems, leading to savings in comparison to formal backup and restore processes.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] Snapshots can also be cloned to form new independent file systems.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] ZFS also has the ability to take a pool level snapshot (known as a "checkpoint"), which allows rollback of operations that may affect the entire pool's structure or that add or remove entire datasets.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] In 1987, AT&T Corporation and Sun announced that they were collaborating on a project to merge the most popular Unix variants on the market at that time: Berkeley Software Distribution, UNIX System V, and Xenix.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] This became Unix System V Release 4 (SVR4).
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] The project was released under the name Solaris, which became the successor to SunOS 4 (although SunOS 4.1.*x* micro releases were retroactively named *Solaris 1*).
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] ZFS was designed and implemented by a team at Sun led by Jeff Bonwick, Bill Moore, and Matthew Ahrens.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] It was announced on September 14, 2004, but development started in 2001.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] Source code for ZFS was integrated into the main trunk of Solaris development on October 31, 2005 and released for developers as part of build 27 of OpenSolaris on November 16, 2005.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] In June 2006, Sun announced that ZFS was included in the mainstream 6/06 update to Solaris 10.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] Solaris was originally developed as proprietary software, but Sun Microsystems was an early commercial proponent of open source software and in June 2005 released most of the Solaris codebase under the CDDL license and founded the OpenSolaris open-source project.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] In Solaris 10 6/06 ("U2"), Sun added the ZFS file system and frequently updated ZFS with new features during the next 5 years.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] ZFS was ported to Linux, Mac OS X (continued as MacZFS), and FreeBSD, under this open source license.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] The name at one point was said to stand for "Zettabyte File System", but by 2006, the name was no longer considered to be an abbreviation.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] A ZFS file system can store up to 256 quadrillion zettabytes (ZB).
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] In September 2007, NetApp sued Sun, claiming that ZFS infringed some of NetApp's patents on Write Anywhere File Layout.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] Sun counter-sued in October the same year claiming the opposite.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] The lawsuits were ended in 2010 with an undisclosed settlement.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] Ported versions of ZFS began to appear in 2005.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] After the Sun acquisition by Oracle in 2010, Oracle's version of ZFS became closed source, and the development of open-source versions proceeded independently, coordinated by OpenZFS from 2013.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] A 1999 study showed that neither any of the then-major and widespread filesystems (such as UFS, Ext, XFS, JFS, or NTFS), nor hardware RAID (which has some issues with data integrity) provided sufficient protection against data corruption problems.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] Initial research indicates that ZFS protects data better than earlier efforts.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] It is also faster than UFS and can be seen as its replacement.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] Within ZFS, data integrity is achieved by using a Fletcher-based checksum or a SHA-256 hash throughout the file system tree.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] Each block of data is checksummed and the checksum value is then saved in the pointer to that block—rather than at the actual block itself.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] Next, the block pointer is checksummed, with the value being saved at *its* pointer.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] This checksumming continues all the way up the file system's data hierarchy to the root node, which is also checksummed, thus creating a Merkle tree.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] In-flight data corruption or phantom reads/writes (the data written/read checksums correctly but is actually wrong) are undetectable by most filesystems as they store the checksum with the data.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] ZFS stores the checksum of each block in its parent block pointer so that the entire pool self-validates.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] When a block is accessed, regardless of whether it is data or meta-data, its checksum is calculated and compared with the stored checksum value of what it "should" be.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] It is optionally possible to provide additional in-pool redundancy by specifying copies=2 (or copies=3), which means that data will be stored twice (or three times) on the disk, effectively halving (or, for copies=3, reducing to one-third) the storage capacity of the disk.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] Additionally, some kinds of data used by ZFS to manage the pool are stored multiple times by default for safety even with the default copies=1 setting.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] If other copies of the damaged data exist or can be reconstructed from checksums and parity data, ZFS will use a copy of the data (or recreate it via a RAID recovery mechanism) and recalculate the checksum—ideally resulting in the reproduction of the originally expected value.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] If the data passes this integrity check, the system can then update all faulty copies with known-good data and redundancy will be restored.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] If there are no copies of the damaged data, ZFS puts the pool in a faulted state, preventing its future use and providing no documented ways to recover pool contents.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] Consistency of data held in memory, such as cached data in the ARC, is not checked by default, as ZFS is expected to run on enterprise-quality hardware with error correcting RAM.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] However, the capability to check in-memory data exists and can be enabled using "debug flags".
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] For ZFS to be able to guarantee data integrity, it needs multiple copies of the data or parity information, usually spread across multiple disks.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] This is typically achieved by using either a RAID controller or so-called "soft" RAID (built into a file system).
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] While ZFS *can* work with hardware RAID devices, it functions more efficiently and with greater data protection when provided with raw access to all storage devices.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] ZFS relies on direct communication with the disk to determine the moment data is confirmed as safely written and has numerous algorithms designed to optimize its use of caching, cache flushing, and disk handling.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] Disks connected to the system using a hardware, firmware, other "soft" RAID, or any other controller that modifies the ZFS-to-disk I/O path will affect ZFS performance and data integrity.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] The hardware RAID card will interfere with ZFS's algorithms.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] RAID controllers also usually add controller-dependent data to the drives which prevents software RAID from accessing the user data.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] In the case of a hardware RAID controller failure, it may be possible to read the data with another compatible controller, but this isn't always possible and a replacement may not be available.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] Alternate hardware RAID controllers may not understand the original manufacturer's custom data required to manage and restore an array.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] Unlike most other systems where RAID cards or similar hardware can offload resources and processing to enhance performance and reliability, with ZFS it is strongly recommended that these methods *not* be used as they typically *reduce* the system's performance and reliability.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] Instead of hardware RAID, ZFS employs "soft" RAID, offering *RAID-Z* (parity based like RAID 5 and similar) and disk mirroring (similar to RAID 1).
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] RAID-Z is a data/parity distribution scheme like RAID-5, but uses dynamic stripe width: every block is its own RAID stripe, regardless of blocksize, resulting in every RAID-Z write being a full-stripe write.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] RAID-Z is also faster than traditional RAID 5 because it does not need to perform the usual read-modify-write sequence.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] As all stripes are of different sizes, RAID-Z reconstruction has to traverse the filesystem metadata to determine the actual RAID-Z geometry.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] RAID-Z and mirroring do not require any special hardware: they do not need NVRAM for reliability, and they do not need write buffering for quality performance or data protection.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] The need for RAID-Z3 arose in the early 2000s as multi-terabyte capacity drives became more common.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] This increase in capacity—without a corresponding increase in throughput speeds—meant that rebuilding an array due to a failed drive could "easily take weeks or months" to complete.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] During this time, the older disks in the array will be stressed by the additional workload, which could result in data corruption or drive failure.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] By increasing parity, RAID-Z3 reduces the chance of data loss by simply increasing redundancy.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] ZFS has no tool equivalent to fsck (the standard Unix and Linux data checking and repair tool for file systems).
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] Instead, ZFS has a built-in scrub function which regularly examines all data and repairs silent corruption and other problems.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] The official recommendation from Sun/Oracle is to scrub enterprise-level disks once a month, and cheaper commodity disks once a week.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] ZFS is a 128-bit file system, so it can address 1.84 × 1019 times more data than 64-bit systems such as Btrfs.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] The maximum limits of ZFS are designed to be so large that they should never be encountered in practice.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] For instance, fully populating a single zpool with 2128 bits of data would require 3×1024 TB hard disk drives.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] With Oracle Solaris, the encryption capability in ZFS is embedded into the I/O pipeline.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] During writes, a block may be compressed, encrypted, checksummed and then deduplicated, in that order.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] The policy for encryption is set at the dataset level when datasets (file systems or ZVOLs) are created.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] The wrapping keys provided by the user/administrator can be changed at any time without taking the file system offline.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] The default behaviour is for the wrapping key to be inherited by any child data sets.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] The data encryption keys are randomly generated at dataset creation time.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] Only descendant datasets (snapshots and clones) share data encryption keys.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] A command to switch to a new data encryption key for the clone or at any time is provided—this does not re-encrypt already existing data, instead utilising an encrypted master-key mechanism.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] As of 2019 the encryption feature is also fully integrated into OpenZFS 0.8.0 available for Debian and Ubuntu Linux distributions.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] There have been anecdotal end-user reports of failures when using ZFS native encryption.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] An exact cause has not been established.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] ZFS will automatically allocate data storage across all vdevs in a pool (and all devices in each vdev) in a way that generally maximises the performance of the pool.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] ZFS will also update its write strategy to take account of new disks added to a pool, when they are added.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] As a general rule, ZFS allocates writes across vdevs based on the free space in each vdev.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] This ensures that vdevs which have proportionately less data already, are given more writes when new data is to be stored.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] This helps to ensure that as the pool becomes more used, the situation does not develop that some vdevs become full, forcing writes to occur on a limited number of devices.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] It also means that when data is read (and reads are much more frequent than writes in most uses), different parts of the data can be read from as many disks as possible at the same time, giving much higher read performance.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] Therefore, as a general rule, pools and vdevs should be managed and new storage added, so that the situation does not arise that some vdevs in a pool are almost full and others almost empty, as this will make the pool less efficient.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] Free space in ZFS tends to become fragmented with usage.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] ZFS does not have a mechanism for defragmenting free space.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] There are anecdotal end-user reports of diminished performance when high free-space fragmentation is coupled with disk space over-utilization.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] Pools can have hot spares to compensate for failing disks.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] When mirroring, block devices can be grouped according to physical chassis, so that the filesystem can continue in the case of the failure of an entire chassis.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] Storage pool composition is not limited to similar devices, but can consist of ad-hoc, heterogeneous collections of devices, which ZFS seamlessly pools together, subsequently doling out space to datasets (file system instances or ZVOLs) as needed.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] Arbitrary storage device types can be added to existing pools to expand their size.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] The storage capacity of all vdevs is available to all of the file system instances in the zpool.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] A quota can be set to limit the amount of space a file system instance can occupy, and a reservation can be set to guarantee that space will be available to a file system instance.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] ZFS uses different layers of disk cache to speed up read and write operations.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] Ideally, all data should be stored in RAM, but that is usually too expensive.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] Therefore, data is automatically cached in a hierarchy to optimize performance versus cost; these are often called "hybrid storage pools".
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] Frequently accessed data will be stored in RAM, and less frequently accessed data can be stored on slower media, such as solid-state drives (SSDs).
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] Data that is not often accessed is not cached and left on the slow hard drives.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] If old data is suddenly read a lot, ZFS will automatically move it to SSDs or to RAM.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] ZFS caching mechanisms include one each for reads and writes, and in each case, two levels of caching can exist, one in computer memory (RAM) and one on fast storage (usually solid-state drives (SSDs)), for a total of four caches.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] A number of other caches, cache divisions, and queues also exist within ZFS.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] For example, each VDEV has its own data cache, and the ARC cache is divided between data stored by the user and metadata used by ZFS, with control over the balance between these.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] In OpenZFS 0.8 and later, it is possible to configure a Special VDEV class to preferentially store filesystem metadata, and optionally the Data Deduplication Table (DDT), and small filesystem blocks.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] This allows, for example, to create a Special VDEV on fast solid-state storage to store the metadata, while the regular file data is stored on spinning disks.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] This speeds up metadata-intensive operations such as filesystem traversal, scrub, and resilver, without the expense of storing the entire filesystem on solid-state storage.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] ZFS uses a copy-on-write transactional object model.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] All block pointers within the filesystem contain a 256-bit checksum or 256-bit hash (currently a choice between Fletcher-2, Fletcher-4, or SHA-256) of the target block, which is verified when the block is read.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] Blocks containing active data are never overwritten in place; instead, a new block is allocated, modified data is written to it, then any metadata blocks referencing it are similarly read, reallocated, and written.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] To reduce the overhead of this process, multiple updates are grouped into transaction groups, and ZIL (intent log) write cache is used when synchronous write semantics are required.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] The blocks are arranged in a tree, as are their checksums (see Merkle signature scheme).
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] An advantage of copy-on-write is that, when ZFS writes new data, the blocks containing the old data can be retained, allowing a snapshot version of the file system to be maintained.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] ZFS snapshots are consistent (they reflect the entire data as it existed at a single point in time), and can be created extremely quickly, since all the data composing the snapshot is already stored, with the entire storage pool often snapshotted several times per hour.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] They are also space efficient, since any unchanged data is shared among the file system and its snapshots.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] Snapshots are inherently read-only, ensuring they will not be modified after creation, although they should not be relied on as a sole means of backup.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] Entire snapshots can be restored and also files and directories within snapshots.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] Writable snapshots ("clones") can also be created, resulting in two independent file systems that share a set of blocks.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] As changes are made to any of the clone file systems, new data blocks are created to reflect those changes, but any unchanged blocks continue to be shared, no matter how many clones exist.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] This is an implementation of the copy-on-write principle.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] ZFS file systems can be moved to other pools, also on remote hosts over the network, as the send command creates a stream representation of the file system's state.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] This stream can either describe complete contents of the file system at a given snapshot, or it can be a delta between snapshots.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] Computing the delta stream is very efficient, and its size depends on the number of blocks changed between the snapshots.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] This provides an efficient strategy, e.g., for synchronizing offsite backups or high availability mirrors of a pool.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] Dynamic striping across all devices to maximize throughput means that as additional devices are added to the zpool, the stripe width automatically expands to include them; thus, all disks in a pool are used, which balances the write load across them.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] ZFS uses variable-sized blocks, with 128 KB as the default size.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] Available features allow the administrator to tune the maximum block size which is used, as certain workloads do not perform well with large blocks.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] If data compression is enabled, variable block sizes are used.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] If a block can be compressed to fit into a smaller block size, the smaller size is used on the disk to use less storage and improve IO throughput (though at the cost of increased CPU use for the compression and decompression operations).
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] In ZFS, filesystem manipulation within a storage pool is easier than volume manipulation within a traditional filesystem; the time and effort required to create or expand a ZFS filesystem is closer to that of making a new directory than it is to volume manipulation in some other systems.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] Pools and their associated ZFS file systems can be moved between different platform architectures, including systems implementing different byte orders.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] The ZFS block pointer format stores filesystem metadata in an endian-adaptive way; individual metadata blocks are written with the native byte order of the system writing the block.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] When reading, if the stored endianness does not match the endianness of the system, the metadata is byte-swapped in memory.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] This does not affect the stored data; as is usual in POSIX systems, files appear to applications as simple arrays of bytes, so applications creating and reading data remain responsible for doing so in a way independent of the underlying system's endianness.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] Data deduplication capabilities were added to the ZFS source repository at the end of October 2009, and relevant OpenSolaris ZFS development packages have been available since December 3, 2009 (build 128).
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] Effective use of deduplication may require large RAM capacity; recommendations range between 1 and 5 GB of RAM for every TB of storage.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] An accurate assessment of the memory required for deduplication is made by referring to the number of unique blocks in the pool, and the number of bytes on disk and in RAM ("core") required to store each record—these figures are reported by inbuilt commands such as `zpool` and `zdb`.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] Insufficient physical memory or lack of ZFS cache can result in virtual memory thrashing when using deduplication, which can cause performance to plummet, or result in complete memory starvation.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] Because deduplication occurs at write-time, it is also very CPU-intensive and this can also significantly slow down a system.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] Other storage vendors use modified versions of ZFS to achieve very high data compression ratios.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] Two examples in 2012 were GreenBytes and Tegile.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] In May 2014, Oracle bought GreenBytes for its ZFS deduplication and replication technology.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] As described above, deduplication is usually *not* recommended due to its heavy resource requirements (especially RAM) and impact on performance (especially when writing), other than in specific circumstances where the system and data are well-suited to this space-saving technique.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] ZFS does not ship with tools such as fsck, because the file system itself was designed to self-repair.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p01] So long as a storage pool had been built with sufficient attention to the design of storage and redundancy of data, basic tools like fsck were never required.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p02] Oracle Corporation ceased the public development of both ZFS and OpenSolaris after the acquisition of Sun in 2010.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p02] Some developers forked the last public release of OpenSolaris as the Illumos project.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p02] Because of the significant advantages present in ZFS, it has been ported to several different platforms with different features and commands.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p02] For coordinating the development efforts and to avoid fragmentation, OpenZFS was founded in 2013.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p02] According to Matt Ahrens, one of the main architects of ZFS, over 50% of the original OpenSolaris ZFS code has been replaced in OpenZFS with community contributions as of 2019, making “Oracle ZFS” and “OpenZFS” politically and technologically incompatible.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p02] In January 2010, Oracle Corporation acquired Sun Microsystems, and quickly discontinued the OpenSolaris distribution and the open source development model.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p02] In August 2010, Oracle discontinued providing public updates to the source code of the Solaris OS/Networking repository, effectively turning Solaris 11 back into a closed source proprietary operating system.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p02] The original plan explicitly stated that illumos would not be a distribution or a fork.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p02] However, after Oracle announced discontinuing OpenSolaris, plans were made to fork the final version of the Solaris ON, allowing illumos to evolve into an operating system of its own.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p02] As part of OpenSolaris, an open source version of ZFS was therefore integral within illumos.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p02] ZFS was widely used within numerous platforms, as well as Solaris.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p02] Therefore, in 2013, the co-ordination of development work on the open source version of ZFS was passed to an umbrella project, *OpenZFS*.
[src:zfs-filesystem/zfs-p02] The OpenZFS framework allows any interested parties to collaboratively develop the core ZFS codebase in common, while individually maintaining any specific extra code which ZFS requires to function and integrate within their own systems.
